  "title": "Never take investment advice from someone who has to work for a living",
  "text": "Never trust someone who teaches swimming but’s afraid to get wet.\nReal advice comes from those who’ve drowned before—and now swim in their own capital.\nMost people giving you money advice… need money.\nAnd that changes everything.\nTV sells you gurus.\nLinkedIn sells you formulas.\nTikTok? Every intern thinks they’re a fund manager.\nBut real investors don’t sell courses.\nThey don’t have time—they’re busy compounding returns.\nWant to know if the advice is worth anything? Ask yourself:\nDoes this person depend on me—or anyone—to pay next month’s bills?\nIf yes, that “advice” is biased.\nIt’s marketing, not wisdom.\nThe real investor doesn’t operate to pay bills.\nHe operates to multiply a fortune that already bought him freedom.\nIt’s not arrogance. It’s a filter.\nIf you’re building—or defending—an empire, you need voices unshackled from the system, the paycheck, the ego.\nOnly take advice from someone you’d trade places with.\nThe truth is simple—just hard to swallow:\nThose who live off their own capital say little—but think clearly.",
